I completely understand your concern, and I apologize for not being clear. Let me explain the required minimum vs. recommended employer contribution and show you real numbers based on your tight margin situation.

NEW JERSEY LEGAL REQUIREMENTS (What You MUST Pay)
MINIMUM Employer Contribution Required by NJ Law: Only 10%

New Jersey small employer health insurance law requires you to contribute a minimum of only 10% of the total premium. That's it. The 50-75% I mentioned earlier was what's competitive or recommended, NOT what's legally required.

You can legally offer health insurance and only pay 10% while Rajesh pays 90%.

YOUR ACTUAL BUSINESS SITUATION
Let me understand your financials:

Revenue from Client:

Client rate: $66/hour
Rajesh works full-time: ~173 hours/month (assuming full-time)
Total client billing: $66 × 173 = $11,418/month
Your Margin (20%):

Paragroup keeps: $11,418 × 20% = $2,284/month gross margin
Your Current Fixed Costs:

TCI insurance: $870/month
Factoring/invoice fees: $237/month
Workers comp insurance: ~$150-200/month (estimate)
General liability (Hiscox): ~$100-150/month (estimate)
Total current overhead: ~$1,357-1,457/month
What's Left:

Gross margin: $2,284
Minus overhead: -$1,357
Net before health insurance: ~$827-927/month
Now you're being asked to add health insurance on top of this. I totally understand the concern - you're already running thin margins.

HEALTH INSURANCE COST SCENARIOS
Let's say the health insurance quote comes back at $2,400/month total premium for Rajesh's family. Here are your options:

Option 1: Minimum Legal Contribution (10%)
Total monthly premium: $2,400
Your contribution (10%): $240/month
Rajesh pays (90%): $2,160/month
Impact on your business:

Current net: $927/month
Minus health insurance: -$240/month
New net: $687/month
Impact on Rajesh:

His gross hourly: $52.80/hour ($9,158/month gross)
Minus health insurance: -$2,160/month
Minus payroll taxes: ~-$1,465/month
His take-home: ~$5,533/month
This is tight for him with a family of 4
Option 2: 25% Employer Contribution (More Reasonable)
Total monthly premium: $2,400
Your contribution (25%): $600/month
Rajesh pays (75%): $1,800/month
Impact on your business:

Current net: $927/month
Minus health insurance: -$600/month
New net: $327/month
Impact on Rajesh:

His gross: $9,158/month
Minus health insurance: -$1,800/month
Minus payroll taxes: ~-$1,465/month
His take-home: ~$5,893/month
More manageable for him
Option 3: 50% Employer Contribution (Competitive)
Total monthly premium: $2,400
Your contribution (50%): $1,200/month
Rajesh pays (50%): $1,200/month
Impact on your business:

Current net: $927/month
Minus health insurance: -$1,200/month
New net: -$273/month (you're losing money)
Impact on Rajesh:

His gross: $9,158/month
Minus health insurance: -$1,200/month
Minus payroll taxes: ~-$1,465/month
His take-home: ~$6,493/month
Much better for him, but you can't afford it
THE TAX BENEFIT YOU'RE MISSING
Here's something important: Your employer contribution is 100% tax-deductible as a business expense.

If you pay $240/month (10% contribution):

Business deduction: $240/month × 12 = $2,880/year
Tax savings (assuming 21% corporate rate + state): ~$750/year
Effective cost to you: ~$2,130/year or $178/month
If you pay $600/month (25% contribution):

Business deduction: $600/month × 12 = $7,200/year
Tax savings: ~$1,900/year
Effective cost: ~$5,300/year or $442/month
So the actual impact is lower than the raw numbers suggest.

YOUR REALISTIC OPTIONS
Given your margin situation, here's what I recommend:

OPTION A: Minimum 10% Contribution + Negotiate Rate Increase
What you do:

Offer health insurance with 10% employer contribution (legal minimum)
Rajesh pays 90% of the premium
Simultaneously, negotiate with your client for a rate increase
Rationale:

You're providing insurance (which many small consulting firms don't)
Your cost is only $240-300/month
Rajesh still gets group insurance (better than individual market)
H-1B employees often accept this because they can't get subsidized marketplace coverage
How to present to Rajesh: "Rajesh, I'm offering health insurance through the company. The law requires I pay 10% of the premium, and you'll pay 90% through payroll deduction. This is still better than you buying individual insurance because:

Group rates are typically 15-25% cheaper than individual rates
You can pay with pre-tax dollars (saves you ~30% on taxes)
All pre-existing conditions are covered with no waiting period
It shows continuous group coverage for your visa documents"
OPTION B: 25% Contribution + Small Rate Adjustment
What you do:

Contribute 25% of premium ($600/month)
Ask client for $3/hour rate increase ($66 → $69/hour)
This generates extra $519/month revenue
Almost covers your health insurance cost
Rationale:

More fair split with Rajesh
Shows you're invested in his benefits
Rate increase of 4.5% is reasonable given inflation
Makes you competitive for retaining H-1B talent
How to approach client: "We're enhancing our benefits package to provide health insurance for our consultants. To continue providing the same level of quality service, we need to adjust the rate to $69/hour, a 4.5% increase. This is our first increase since [date] and aligns with market rates."

OPTION C: Performance-Based Contribution
What you do:

Start with 10% base contribution
Increase contribution based on revenue/performance
Example: "I'll pay 10% base, plus an additional 5% for every $50k in quarterly revenue"
Rationale:

Shows you'll share success
Keeps your fixed costs low
Motivates Rajesh to help grow business
Fair to both parties
WHAT RAJESH NEEDS TO UNDERSTAND
The reality is that with H-1B status:

He cannot get marketplace subsidies (only available to citizens/permanent residents)
Individual health insurance would cost him $2,500-3,500/month for family coverage
Through your group plan at $2,400/month total, even if he pays 90% ($2,160), he's saving money
Plus he gets the pre-tax benefit (saves him ~$650/month in taxes)
Net savings to Rajesh even at 90% contribution:

Individual market cost: $3,000/month after-tax dollars
Group plan cost: $2,160/month pre-tax (equivalent to ~$1,510 after-tax)
His savings: ~$1,490/month by being on your group plan
